# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# fac — easy-to-use CUI for fixing git conflicts (Go, 1,857★)
#
# upstream: https://github.com/mkchoi212/fac
# author : Michael Choi (mkchoi212)
# license: MIT
#
# Source-direct completion: every flag below is verbatim from options.go
# on the mkchoi212/fac tip — Go stdlib `flag.Bool` registration parsed
# exactly as declared.  Most of fac's configuration is via a YAML
# config file (`$HOME/.fac.yml`) rather than CLI flags; the only CLI
# flag is `--version`.
#
# Direct deps from go.mod (selected):
#   github.com/alecthomas/chroma  v0.10.0  ← canonical Go syntax
#                                            highlighting library
#                                            (this axis) — by Alec
#                                            Thomas (alecthomas);
#                                            pure-Go port of Python's
#                                            Pygments highlighter
#                                            with 200+ language
#                                            lexers, multiple style
#                                            themes (monokai,
#                                            dracula, etc.), and
#                                            terminal / HTML / SVG
#                                            output formatters.  fac
#                                            uses chroma to render
#                                            conflict regions with
#                                            language-aware
#                                            syntax highlighting in
#                                            the TUI.
#   github.com/jroimartin/gocui              (TUI library — terminal
#                                            UI with panels, key
#                                            bindings, mouse support)
#
# fac is a TUI-based git merge conflict resolver: navigate between
# conflicts, see local vs incoming versions side-by-side (or above/
# below) with syntax-highlighted context via chroma, and pick local
# / incoming / both / neither for each conflict region without
# leaving the terminal.  Key bindings configurable via `$HOME/.fac.
# yml` (see `fac --help` for the full list).
#
# === AXIS 180 CONTINUES — pure-language syntax highlighting libraries =====
# Axis position: Go=235 continues Axis 180 (slot 2/0/0).  Canonical Go
# pure-language syntax highlighting library is `github.com/alecthomas/
# chroma` by Alec Thomas (alecthomas) — pure-Go port of Python's
# Pygments lexer + formatter framework with 200+ language lexers,
# multiple style themes (monokai, dracula, github, vs, paraiso-light/
# dark, swapoff, friendly, etc.), and output formatters for terminal
# (truecolor + 256-color + 8-color fallbacks), HTML (inline styles or
# external CSS), SVG, plain tokens, and JSON.  THE canonical Go syntax
# highlighter — used by Hugo (gohugoio/hugo's `highlight` shortcode),
# gobang, fac, gobyexample, museslabs/kyma, terrastruct/d2 (D2
# diagramming language), and most Go tools that pretty-print source
# code in terminal or HTML output.
#
# Cycle position in current 3+1 micro-cycle:
#   Rust=235     _microbin            ← previous round (axis 180 OPENS, 1/0/0)
#   Go=235       ← THIS FILE          (axis 180 continues, slot 2/0/0)
#   TS-Node=235  ← next round         (axis 180 CLOSES at triple-235, 1/1/1)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

_fac() {
    _arguments -s \
        '(- *)--help[show usage with customizable variables list (cont_eval, select_local, select_incoming, toggle_view, show_up/down, scroll_up/down, edit, next/previous, quit, help)]' \
        '(- *)--version[print the version of fac being run]'
}

_fac "$@"
